## Expected Behavior
Read a png file, get an `array2d<bgr_pixel>` object `A`, use `toMat` function to convert `A` to a OpenCV `Mat` object `B`.
Use A with `equalize_histogram` in dlib, get result `C`.
Use B with `euqalizeHist` in opencv, get result `D`.
(equalizeHist takes only single channel image, so the stage is:

1. split
2. equalizeHist
3. merge

)
C should have same contents with D.

Same as `sobel_edge_detector` and `Sobel`.

I've read the documentation of dlib and OpenCV about equalize histogram, and find its algorithm described is different.
And I've confirmed the logic in source code is actually as the documentation described.

So, my problem is why does this happended?
And especially, same image input go through some "same" function between dlib and opencv, will get a very different result which will make the "right algorithm" ambigious.

## Current Behavior
`C` has different contents with `D`.
use `toMat` to synchronize the content of `C` and `D`, then use `sobel_edge_detector` and `Sobel`, get result `E` and `F`, still no same content.

## Steps to Reproduce
```c++
    array2d<bgr_pixel> img2;
    load_image(img2, im_path);
    array2d<bgr_pixel> resized_img(height, width);
    resize_image(img2, resized_img);

    equalize_histogram(resized_img, eh_img);

    Mat resized_img1 = toMat(resized_img);
    Mat eh_img2(height, width, resized_img1.type());
    std::vector<Mat> resized_img_channels(resized_img1.channels());
    split(resized_img1, resized_img_channels);
    for (int i = 0; i < resized_img_channels.size(); ++i) {
        equalizeHist(resized_img_channels[i], resized_img_channels[i]);
    }
    merge(resized_img_channels, eh_img2);

    array2d<unsigned char> img_gray;
    assign_image(img_gray, eh_img);
    matrix<float> horz_gradient, vert_gradient, edge_image;
    sobel_edge_detector(img_gray, horz_gradient, vert_gradient);
    matrix<float> horz_gradient_, vert_gradient_;
    horz_gradient_ = clamp(horz_gradient, 0.0f, 255.0f) / 255.0f;
    vert_gradient_ = clamp(vert_gradient, 0.0f, 255.0f) / 255.0f;
    matrix<float> product = trans(horz_gradient_) * vert_gradient_;
    double sun_edge = sum(product);
    double source = sun_edge / product.nc() / product.nr();

    Mat img_gray2;
    img_gray2 = toMat(img_gray); //Force contents to be the same.
    Mat horz_gradient_1, vert_gradient_1;
    threshold(horz_gradient1, horz_gradient_1, 255, 255, THRESH_TRUNC);
    threshold(vert_gradient1, vert_gradient_1, 255, 255, THRESH_TRUNC);
    threshold(horz_gradient1, horz_gradient_1, 0, 0, THRESH_TOZERO);
    threshold(vert_gradient1, vert_gradient_1, 0, 0, THRESH_TOZERO);
    horz_gradient_1 /= 255.0;
    vert_gradient_1 /= 255.0;
    Mat prod = horz_gradient_1.t() * vert_gradient_1;
    double sum_edge = cv::sum(prod)[0];
    sum_edge /= (prod.cols * prod.rows);
```
And
`source != sum_edge`

